article.description:
Atlanta coach Terry Stotts made his team stick to
the plan, even after the Hawks fell behind the Cleveland Cavaliers in the first quarter.
article.headline: Atlanta's 26-0 first-quarter run puts away Cleveland
article.linkText: Hawks follow formula to put away Cavs
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta coach Terry Stotts made his team stick to the plan, even after the Hawks fell behind the Cleveland Cavaliers in the first quarter. ''Coach said we just needed to get up by 10, and they'd fold,'' Hawks forward Ira Newble said. ''They didn't want to play if they didn't have a chance to win. So we just had to get it together.'' Six different players scored during Atlanta's 26-0 run in the first quarter, and the Hawks went on to beat Cleveland 109-89 Friday night. The Cavs have lost 20 in a row on the road and fell to 15-64 overall. They dropped all four games to the Hawks this season. ''We weren't even in the gym tonight,'' Cleveland coach Keith Smart said. ''Our guys think they can do it with one jump shot. One guy thinks that, then five do, and pretty soon you're blown out.'' Dion Glover had 20 points, and Theo Ratliff and Shareef Abdur-Rahim scored 17 apiece in only three quarters as the Hawks put all five starters in double figures for the second consecutive game. They won their fourth in a row at home, and fourth out of five overall. Glenn Robinson missed his second consecutive game with a strained Achilles' tendon, and Darvin Ham sat out with the flu. With its 33rd victory of the season, Atlanta matched its total from last year. Reserve guard Tierre Brown had season highs with 15 points and 30 minutes for Cleveland, and Ricky Davis and Jumaine Jones had 13 apiece. With three games left, the Cavaliers need one more victory to avoid tying the worst season in franchise history. Cleveland went 15-67 in 1970-71 -- its inaugural season -- and again in 1981-82. ''We don't want that record,'' center Zydrunas Ilgauskas said. The Cavs took a 10-2 lead in the first quarter, forcing Stotts to call a timeout. Ratliff then hit a jumper to cut the lead to six and, during the next eight minutes, Cleveland missed 12 consecutive shots and five free throws, and also made five turnovers. Jason Terry had seven points during the Hawks' run, and Ratliff and Abdur-Rahim each scored six. With 32 seconds left in the quarter, and his team down 28-10, Smart called a timeout. Terry then stole the inbound pass and fed Alan Henderson for a wide-open layup, but the ball rolled off the rim, and Cleveland raced to the other end. Brown hit a jumper, part of a 3-for-4 half for him, to end the drought. ''We came out and got a little lead and then gave up a 26-0 run,'' Ilgauskas said. ''When you're playing on the road, it's impossible to come back from that.'' It got so bad for the Cavs that Davis complained about the rim after he missed a free throw. Terry stepped up the line and shook his head, signaling that he didn't see a problem, and the referees apparently agreed. After the quarter, a maintenance crew brought out a ladder and a level to check the basket, and they also gave it the OK. Cleveland finished 7-for-15 from the line. ''Normally, we are a decent free throw shooting team,'' Ilgauskas said. ''Not tonight.'' Unfortunately for the Cavs, the remaining three quarters didn't get much better. Their deficit grew to 30 in the third quarter, and only a late run kept the final score a bit more respectable. ''We've emphasized defense and playing hard but the truth is, I think we've become a better offensive team in the second half of the season and that's had a domino effect,'' Stotts said. ''We've played better offense and we've played better defense because of it.'' Game notes
Robinson wasn't expected to travel with the Hawks for the game Saturday night in Washington, but Ham planned to make the trip. ... Atlanta last swept the season series from the Cavaliers in the 1997-98 season. ... Cleveland forward Carlos Boozer had 12 rebounds in only 18 minutes.
